{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context / Problem\n\nToday the reconciler core reaches into the Jira adapter directly (ADR 0035 §(a)/§(b)\ninventory). There is no named interface a second backend could implement. This story introduces\nthat interface — the `Backend` facade, its role Protocols, and the `RemoteRef` identity type\npinned in ADR 0035 §(d) [rebar:ef33-eaf6-a545-4bfb] — plus a backend-agnostic **contract test\nsuite** and a thin `JiraBackend` that wraps today's Jira modules with **zero behavior change**.\nNo core call sites are rewired here (that is S4 [rebar:6673-7636-a116-4f90]); this story only\nlands the port and its first implementation.\n\nEdit-set:\n- New `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/_backend.py` — the `Backend` facade, the five role\n  Protocols (`TicketTransport`, `OutboundMapper`, `InboundMapper`, `FieldSanitizer`,\n  `IdentityConvention`), the three opt-in capability Protocols (`SupportsLinks`,\n  `SupportsComments`, `SupportsIncremental`), and the `RemoteRef{vendor, instance, remote_id}`\n  dataclass. **Capability-detection mechanism (pinned here):** callers (and the contract suite)\n  detect an opt-in capability with `isinstance(backend, SupportsLinks)` /\n  `isinstance(backend, SupportsComments)` / `isinstance(backend, SupportsIncremental)` — the\n  three capability Protocols are declared `@runtime_checkable`, which is already the reconciler's\n  established pattern (`outbound_differ.py:228`, `inbound_differ.py`). There is **no**\n  `capabilities()` method. `FakeBackend` (test-only) exercises the guarded path by *inheriting*\n  the opt-in Protocol and the skip path by *omitting* it — so \"observed via behavior\" means\n  `isinstance`-guarded dispatch, not structural attribute introspection.\n- New `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/adapters/jira/backend.py` — `JiraBackend`, a thin\n  wrapper delegating to the existing Jira modules (`acli.AcliClient`, `outbound_fields`,\n  `inbound_fields`/`inbound_translate`, `adapters/jira/jira_fields.py`, `comment_limits`).\n- New tests: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_backend_contract.py` (the parameterized contract\n  suite), a `FakeBackend`, and characterization tests over the pure Jira mappers.\n\n## Approach\n\nDerive each Protocol's method signatures from the **de-facto surface the core already calls**,\nso `JiraBackend` is a pure delegation shim and no logic moves yet:\n- `TicketTransport` ← the create/read/update/transition/comment methods on `acli.AcliClient`.\n- `OutboundMapper` ← `outbound_fields._map_local_to_jira_fields` (+ `adf.fit_text_to_adf_limit`).\n- `InboundMapper` ← the `inbound_fields`/`inbound_translate` payload→local extraction.\n- `FieldSanitizer` ← `adapters/jira/jira_fields.py` sanitizers + `comment_limits` size-fit.\n- `IdentityConvention` ← the `rebar-id:<local_id>` label read/write convention. Unlike the\n  other four Protocols, this one has **no single existing function to delegate to** — the\n  convention is currently *inlined* at four core call sites: the write is\n  `client.add_label(…, f\"rebar-id:{local_id}\")` at `dispatch_one.py:320`,\n  `binding_store.py:516`, and `apply_inbound_records.py:223`, and the read is the\n  `\"rebar-id:\"`/`\"rebar-id-\"` prefix scan at `binding_walk.py:341`. So S2 introduces\n  `IdentityConvention` as a **new, self-contained pure convention object under\n  `adapters/jira/`** that formats a `RemoteRef` → the `rebar-id:{remote_id}` label string and\n  parses that label back to a `RemoteRef` (the single source of the format those four sites\n  currently hand-inline). It is **not** a delegation shim over existing core code, and the four\n  core call sites are **not** rewired to it here — routing them through\n  `IdentityConvention` is S4 [rebar:6673-7636-a116-4f90]. The S2 contract test exercises the\n  convention object directly (stamp a `RemoteRef` → label string; parse label string →\n  `RemoteRef`; round-trip), needing no transport and touching no core module.\n\n**Driving the contract suite without a live Jira** uses the pattern already established in the\napply tests: inject a fake transport\n(`types.SimpleNamespace(AcliClient=lambda **_: mock_client)`, as in\n`tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/apply/test_applier_mapping.py:157`). The contract suite is\nparameterized over a `backend_factory` fixture and run against both `JiraBackend` (transport =\nthat injected mock) and an in-memory `FakeBackend` (test-only; lives under `tests/`, never\nshipped). The **mapping** contracts assert against the pure mapper functions\n(`_map_local_to_jira_fields`, `adf.fit_text_to_adf_limit`, inbound extraction), which need no\ntransport at all. TDD-held-out: the contract + characterization tests are authored and seen RED\nfirst, then `JiraBackend` is implemented to green.\n\n## Scope\n\n- The `_backend.py` port module (five role Protocols + three capability Protocols + `RemoteRef`).\n- `JiraBackend` thin wrapper (delegation only — no field-mapping logic relocated; that is S4).\n- The contract suite (driven by an injected mock transport + `FakeBackend`) + characterization\n  tests over the pure mappers.\n- **Out of scope:** rewiring any core call site or construction site (S4); the registry / config\n  selection (S3 [rebar:94f9-a9a0-7475-4e75]); physically moving the vendor modules (S5\n  [rebar:dfb9-d2d1-455d-48d9]); any real second backend (epic `be74`).\n\n## Testing\n\n- **Tier:** unit + contract, RED-first (held-out oracle per rebar-implement).\n- **Contract suite** (backend-agnostic, run against `JiraBackend` with an injected mock\n  transport and against `FakeBackend`): outbound map→inbound unmap round-trips to the same local\n  fields the reconciler syncs; the sanitizer enforces label/comment limits and is idempotent;\n  `IdentityConvention` stamps and finds a `RemoteRef`; a capability Protocol's methods are\n  exercised only when the backend advertises it (observed via behavior — a backend that does not\n  implement `SupportsLinks` is never asked to sync links), not via structural introspection.\n- **Characterization tests** pin the **exact current** outputs of the pure Jira mappers\n  (`_map_local_to_jira_fields`, `adf.fit_text_to_adf_limit`, inbound extraction) for\n  representative tickets, proving `JiraBackend` delegation is behavior-preserving.\n- **Teeth:** perturb a `JiraBackend` delegation (e.g. drop the priority map) and confirm a\n  contract/characterization test goes RED, then restore.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `_backend.py` defines `Backend`, the five role Protocols, the three capability Protocols\n  (`SupportsLinks`, `SupportsComments`, `SupportsIncremental`), and `RemoteRef` — importable via\n  `from rebar._engine.rebar_reconciler._backend import Backend, RemoteRef` (verified by an\n  import test that asserts each name resolves and `RemoteRef(vendor=…, instance=…, remote_id=…)`\n  constructs).\n- [ ] `JiraBackend` implements `Backend`; the contract suite passes when parameterized over\n  **both** `JiraBackend` (injected mock transport) and `FakeBackend` — verified by `make test`\n  running the suite twice via the `backend_factory` fixture.\n- [ ] Characterization tests assert the pure Jira mapper outputs are byte-for-byte identical to\n  pre-story `main` for the representative fixtures — verified by literal expected values captured\n  from current behavior (a diff of the captured vs. produced dict is empty).\n- [ ] No core differ/apply module is modified by this story — verified by `git diff --name-only`\n  touching only `_backend.py`, `adapters/jira/backend.py`, and files under `tests/`.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` all green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784738688469548001,"uuid":"0174ece7-1be7-4823-a524-496620360f95"}